{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 15:34:44.768250", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Diagnostic report — SDN spine–leaf lab\\nSummary\\n- Observed a network-wide forwarding failure for hosts in the 10.0.0.0/24 subnets: hosts cannot ARP/communicate with each other (pings return \"Destination Host Unreachable\" and ARP entries are incomplete).\\n- Underlying physical links on host interfaces and switch management interfaces appear up.\\n- All OVS switches have a controller target configured (tcp:20.0.0.100:6633) but fail to establish a controller connection. One leaf reports explicit \"Connection refused\" and state=BACKOFF.\\n- Likely root cause: the OpenFlow controller at 20.0.0.100:6633 is not accepting connections (controller down or refusing), and the switches/OVS bridges are effectively not forwarding host L2 traffic (fail-mode behavior), producing the host-level isolation.\\n\\nEvidence and key outputs (collected)\\n1) Host-to-host ping failures and ARP failures\\n- Ping from host_1_1 to host_2_1:\\n  - Output: \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\" (4/4 lost)\\n- Ping from host_1_1 to host_1_2 (same leaf):\\n  - Output: \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\" (4/4 lost)\\n- host_1_1 neighbor table and ARP:\\n  - ip neigh: \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\" and \"10.0.0.9 dev eth0 FAILED\"\\n  - arp -n / /proc/net/arp: entries for 10.0.0.2 and 10.0.0.9 are \"(incomplete)\" / HW address 00:00:00:00:00:00\\n  => Host cannot resolve local MACs by ARP, so cannot forward IP packets.\\n\\n2) Host physical link is up (rules out physical cabling at host iface)\\n- host_1_1 ethtool eth0: \"Link detected: yes\", Speed: 10000Mb/s, Duplex: Full\\n  => interface operational at physical layer.\\n\\n3) OVS switch controller configuration and connection failure\\n- leaf_1 ovs-vsctl show (controller info):\\n  - target: \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\"\\n  - status: {last_error=\"Connection refused\", sec_since_connect=\"154\", sec_since_disconnect=\"1\", state=BACKOFF}\\n  - bridge \"leaf_1\" shown in state DOWN\\n- leaf_2 and spine_1:\\n  - ovs-vsctl show shows controller target \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" as well\\n  - bridges are present but the ovs-system / logical bridge states are not in a normal \"UP/connected\" state (ovs-system shown DOWN for bridges)\\n  => switches are configured to use the controller, but controller connections are failing/refused.\\n\\n4) Management network interfaces are up and carrying traffic\\n- leaf_1 eth12: inet 20.0.0.5 — RX packets 759, TX packets 37\\n- leaf_2 eth12: inet 20.0.0.6 — RX packets 854, TX packets 38\\n- spine_1 eth8: inet 20.0.0.1 — RX packets 819, TX packets 42\\n  => The switches’ management IPs are configured and the management network appears reachable at L3 between switches, yet controller TCP connect attempts were refused (per leaf_1 last_error).\\n\\nAffected components (localized)\\n- Hosts: host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2 (and by extension all hosts attached to the leaf switches in 10.0.0.0/24) — symptom: cannot ARP or reach other hosts.\\n- Leaf switches: leaf_1, leaf_2 — symptoms: OVS bridges in DOWN state, controller connection failure (leaf_1 shows Connection refused).\\n- Spine switch: spine_1 — configured with same controller target, bridge not operating as expected.\\n- Controller: 20.0.0.100:6633 — implicated as the point of failure (switches are unable to connect and report connection refused).\\n\\nRoot-cause analysis (most likely)\\n- The immediate proximate cause of host isolation is that OVS switches are not functioning as forwarding/learning L2 devices in this deployment because they are dependent on the SDN controller; with the controller unreachable/refusing connections their dataplane is not forwarding host frames (ARP fails).\\n- The controller at 20.0.0.100:6633 is refusing TCP connections (explicitly reported by leaf_1: \"Connection refused\"). Possible explanations (not exhaustive): controller process not running, controller listening on a different TCP port/address, firewall blocking connection, or controller overloaded/refusing new connections. Because the switch management interfaces are up and show traffic, generic IP connectivity to the management network exists; the failure is specifically at the controller/service endpoint.\\n- Because physical interfaces on hosts and switch ports are up (ethtool and interface UP states), a physical link failure is unlikely. The problem is at control-plane level (controller unreachable) causing dataplane forwarding to be disabled or restricted.\\n\\nImpact\\n- Hosts in the 10.0.0.0/24 subnets cannot communicate with each other (no ARP resolution, 100% packet loss for ping attempts).\\n- The SDN control-plane is disrupted: switches are in BACKOFF/unconnected state to the controller; network forwarding is impaired.\\n\\nAdditional observations / contextual notes\\n- The lab topology shows the controller is expected at 20.0.0.100. The switches show management IPs and are attempting to reach that controller.\\n- leaf_1 explicitly records the controller connection error; similar configuration is present on leaf_2 and spine_1 (they share the controller target).\\n- The issue is consistent across leaf and spine switches, pointing to a central control-plane (controller) problem rather than multiple independent switch hardware faults.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- There is a clear anomaly: complete L2/L3 host isolation within the 10.0.0.0/24 host subnets.\\n- Localization: the problem localizes to the SDN control plane and the switches\\' inability to connect to it (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1 affected). Hosts/interfaces themselves are up but cannot ARP due to switches not forwarding.\\n- Root cause hypothesis: the OpenFlow controller at 20.0.0.100:6633 is refusing connections or is down. As a result switches are in BACKOFF/unconnected state and the OVS bridges are not forwarding host traffic in the current fail-mode, leading to host-level connectivity failure.\\n\\nIf you want, I can next:\\n- test TCP reachability (e.g., attempt to connect to 20.0.0.100:6633) from one of the switches to confirm controller is refusing at TCP level, and/or\\n- collect ovs logs (ovsdb/ovs-switchd) and switch log outputs to further confirm controller-side vs switch-side causes,\\n- inspect controller host (if accessible) for process/listener status.\\n\\n(No mitigation steps included per request.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='733fc10b-ecfe-450a-8a13-e32fa734e33e'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
